eshape a fundamentally provincial city. The Culture Broker brings to light the influence of L.A.'s powerful families and chronicles the mixed motives behind large public endeavors. Channeling more than one billion dollars into the city's arts and educational infrastructure, Franklin Murphy elevated Los Angeles to a vibrant world-class city positioned for its role in the new era of global trade and cross-cultural arts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCultural propertyzCaliforniazLos Angeles. 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / West (AK, CA, CO, HI, ID, MT, NV, UT, WY).2bisacsh  aacademia.  aahmanson.  aangeles county museum.  aannenberg.  acalifornia history.  acalifornia university system.  acalifornia.  achancellor.  acollege.  acultural development.  aeducational infrastructure.  aford.  afranklin murphy.  ahigher education.  aindustrial revolution.  aindustry.  alos angeles.  amedia.  amellon.  anewspaper.  anonfiction.  arobber barons.  arockefeller.  atimes mirror.  aucla.  auniversity.  aurban development.  awealth.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052022495740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092555740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520925557423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520925557/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY